  "response": "The relative ratios of brain waves differ between rhesus monkeys and humans, with some notable variations across different brain states and regions. Here's a comparative overview:\n\n1. Alpha Waves (8-12 Hz):\n- Humans: More prominent during relaxed, wakeful states\n- Rhesus Monkeys: Less pronounced, less consistent alpha activity\n\n2. Beta Waves (13-30 Hz):\n- Humans: Dominant during active thinking and concentration\n- Rhesus Monkeys: Similar patterns, but potentially lower overall amplitude\n\n3. Gamma Waves (30-100 Hz):\n- Humans: Associated with higher cognitive processing\n- Rhesus Monkeys: Present, but potentially less complex integration\n\n4. Delta Waves (0.5-4 Hz):\n- Humans: Prominent during deep sleep\n- Rhesus Monkeys: Similar characteristics, but potential subtle differences in amplitude and distribution\n\n5. Theta Waves (4-8 Hz):\n- Humans: Associated with memory and emotional processing\n- Rhesus Monkeys: Similar range, but potentially different functional significance\n\nKey differences arise from variations in cortical complexity, neuronal connectivity, and cognitive processing capabilities between species.\n\nNote: Precise quantitative comparisons require extensive neurophysiological research.",
